i mean i've only been drawing since like march so i don't know if this works for everyone but whenever I feel stuck i either try to copy a professional artist or do targeted exercises to pinpoint where exactly im going wrong

instead of going from starting point > ??? > final product, we can inverse the process, break down the final product in simple shapes and see how value, shapes, medium and composition impacts the things we create to figure out what the ??? is we need to learn.

although some people can figure out themselves what the thing is that's causing them to stagnate, others need specific guidance in noticing their blind spots (which is perfectly fine!)

i have a hard time drawing lips and i would rather avoid them at all times. however, lipless humans aren't really a thing so its in my best interest to draw 10 lips a day to get over this irrational fear, than procrastinate and be able to draw a 10/10 head and 1/10 lips

>something has to change
you'd be surprised how at many people will stagnate for decades, thinking that they're doing "everything" to change while they're hating their art but not improving

the reason i mentioned those artists is that in renaissance drawings, an incredible amount of emphasis is placed on value and forms, and you can see how the artist "paints" in the simplest of sketches compared to how bland and flat art was just 150 years prior - so i feel like you'll be able to take away a lot in terms of value with your painting ambitions (if i recall correctly :))

with drawing heads, we can be very formulaic in our approach (hampton, loomis) or we can eyeball something and redraw and experiment to see what looks "right" based on our understanding of flow - either method has their own benefits and drawbacks

one thing to keep in mind is that the features of the face are subject to the planar changes of the skull itself; you can't just draw an eye on a skull as if it was independent of the underlying structure in 2d
